      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0844">
               <p><persName>Mary</persName>, the oldest daughter of <persName>Bernard
                     Granville</persName> and <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0843.xml"/>Mary
                     (Westcomb) Granville</persName>, was the niece of <persName>George
                     Granville</persName>, Lord Lansdowne, and was a familiar figure in court and
                  literary circles. Her uncle used some pressure to secure her marriage in <date
                     when="1718">1718</date> to the wealthy and elderly <persName>Alexander
                     Pendarves</persName>, who died in <date when="1725">1725</date>. As a widow she
                  often visited her mother and sister in <placeName>Buckland</placeName>, becoming
                  part of the network of Cotswolds friends of <persName><ptr
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and <persName><ptr
                        target="/persons/pers2177.xml"/>CW</persName> during their Oxford years.
                     <persName>Mary</persName>&apos;s literary nickname was
                     &apos;<persName>Aspasia</persName>&apos;, which appears in several of
                        <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s letters
                  of the time. In <date when="1743">1743</date>, after the Cotswolds group had
                  scattered, <persName>Mary</persName> became the second wife of <persName>Patrick
                     Delany</persName>, the intimate friend of <persName>Jonathan Swift</persName>.
                  She corresponded with many of the leading cultural figures of the day. Her
                  greatest artistic achievement were her pages of cut paper illustrations of flowers
                  and plants, which are now in the British Museum. See <hi rend="italic"
                  >ODNB</hi>.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
